<paper id="1548392907"><title>Concurrent Objects in a Process Calculus</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="University of Edinburgh," id="1988947184">Benjamin C. Pierce</author></authors><n_citation>106</n_citation><doc_type /><references><reference>1494146939</reference><reference>1534508664</reference><reference>1571962375</reference><reference>1584334623</reference><reference>1591694044</reference><reference>1596502640</reference><reference>1604697653</reference><reference>1611055354</reference><reference>1790031272</reference><reference>1829244603</reference><reference>2013672985</reference><reference>2037564214</reference><reference>2090959968</reference><reference>2128932399</reference><reference>2138839382</reference><reference>2145782124</reference><reference>2157598146</reference><reference>2170626879</reference></references><venue id="" type="">TPPP '94 Proceedings of the International Workshop on Theory and Practice of Parallel Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0026570</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.65601">Relational calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.46801">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.69827">Typed lambda calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.56478">Concurrency</keyword><keyword weight="0.4475">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.63629">Proof calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.54782">Programming style</keyword><keyword weight="0.68026">Calculus of communicating systems</keyword><keyword weight="0.50389">Operator (computer programming)</keyword><keyword weight="0.70165">Process calculus</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A programming style based on concurrent objects arises almost inevitably in languages where processes communicate by exchanging data on channels. Using the pict language as an experimental testbed, we introduce a simple object-based programming style and compare three techniques for controlling concurrency between methods in this setting: explicit l